'''9 to 5''' is a phrase which refers to the time (''9:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m.'', or ''09:00h to 17:00h'') at which many office employees work each day, usually from Monday to Friday. These hours are the standard business hours in the [[United States]] and [[United Kingdom]], as well as other countries, and are an incarnation of the [[eight-hour day]].  The term ''9 to 5'' is also used as a [[slang]] term for a [[day job]]; for example, "My ''9 to 5'' is at a law office, but my real love is playing in the band."

It is also more commonly used in a way where a person is not simple, dull, or works in an office (which would be considered boring and meaningless in the following way): ''"I'm not exactly a nine-to-five guy"'' ([[George Clooney]] said this line in ''[[Out of Sight]]'').

The phrase became the title of two different songs: "[[9 to 5 (Dolly Parton song)|9 to 5]]" by [[Dolly Parton]] and "[[9 to 5 (Sheena Easton song)|9 to 5]]" by [[Sheena Easton]], which was re-titled "Morning Train (9 to 5)" for its North American release. It is also the title of a new release which is a joint collaboration between [[The Ordinary Boys]] and [[Lady Sovereign]]. The track will be titled "Nine2Five" and it is a re-release of an earlier tack by [[Lady Sovereign]].

"9 to 5" also refers to the name of a 1980 [[film|movie]] (specifically ''[[Nine to Five]]'') starring [[Dolly Parton]], [[Jane Fonda]], and [[Lily Tomlin]], for which Parton's above-referenced song served as a theme song.  The movie was followed by a short-lived [[television series|TV series]] called ''9 to 5''.

